The '''Hungarian occupation of Yugoslav territories''' was the [[military occupation]] then [[annexation]] of the [[Ba<U+010D>ka]], [[Baranja]], [[Me<U+0111>imurje]] and [[Prekmurje]] regions of the [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]] by [[Kingdom of Hungary (1920<U+2013>1946)|Hungary]] during [[World War II]]. These territories had all been under [[Lands of the Crown of Saint Stephen|Hungarian rule]] prior to 1920, and had been transferred to Yugoslavia as part of the post-[[World War I]] [[Treaty of Trianon]]. They now form part of several states: Yugoslav Ba<U+010D>ka is now part of [[Vojvodina]], an autonomous province of [[Serbia]], Yugoslav Baranja and Me<U+0111>imurje are part of modern-day [[Croatia]], and Yugoslav Prekmurje is part of modern-day [[Slovenia]]. The occupation began on 11 April 1941 when 80,000 Hungarian troops crossed the Yugoslav border in support of the [[Nazi Germany|German]]-led [[Axis invasion of Yugoslavia]] that had commenced five days earlier. There was some resistance to the Hungarian forces from [[Serbs in Vojvodina|Serb]] [[Chetnik]] irregulars, but the defences of the [[Royal Yugoslav Army]] had collapsed by this time. The Hungarian forces were indirectly aided by the local ''[[Volksdeutsche]]'', the [[Germans of Yugoslavia|German minority]], which had formed a militia and disarmed around 90,000 Yugoslav troops. Despite only sporadic resistance, Hungarian troops killed many civilians during these initial operations, including some ''Volksdeutsche''. The government of the newly formed [[Axis powers|Axis]] [[puppet state]], the [[Independent State of Croatia]] (NDH), consented to the Hungarian annexation of the Me<U+0111>imurje area, which dismayed the Croat population of the region.

The occupation authorities immediately classified the population of Ba<U+010D>ka and Baranja into those that had lived in those regions when they had last been under Hungarian rule in 1920 and the mostly Serb settlers who had arrived since the areas had been part of Yugoslavia. They then began collecting thousands of Serb members of the population into [[concentration camp]]s and expelled them to the NDH, [[Kingdom of Montenegro (1941<U+2013>1944)|Montenegro]], and the [[Territory of the Military Commander in Serbia]], ultimately deporting tens of thousands of Serbs from the occupied territories. This was followed by the implementation of a policy of "[[magyarisation]]" of the political, social and economic life of the occupied territories, which included the re-settlement of Hungarians and [[Sz<U+00E9>kelys of Bukovina|Sz<U+00E9>kelys]] from other parts of Hungary. "Magyarisation" did not impact the ''Volksdeutsche'', who received special status under Hungarian rule, and in Prekmurje the Hungarian authorities were more permissive towards ethnic Slovenes.

Small-scale armed resistance to the Hungarian occupation commenced in the latter half of 1941 and was answered with harsh measures, including summary executions, expulsions and internment. The insurgency was mainly concentrated in the ethnic-Serb area of southern Ba<U+010D>ka in the [[<U+0160>ajka<U+0161>ka]] region, where Hungarian forces avenged their losses. In August 1941 a civilian administration took over the government of the "Recovered Southern Territories" ({{lang-hu|D<U+00E9>lvid<U+00E9>k}}), and they were formally annexed to Hungary in December. In January 1942 the Hungarian military conducted raids during which they killed over 3,300 people, mostly Serbs and Jews.

In March 1944, when Hungary realised that it was on the losing side in the war and began to negotiate with the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]], Germany took control of the country, including the annexed territories, during [[Operation Margarethe|Operation Margarethe I]]. This was followed by the collection and transport of the remaining Jews in the occupied territories to [[extermination camp]]s, resulting in the deaths of 85 per cent of the Jews in the occupied territories. Prior to their withdrawal from the Balkans in the face of the advance of the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[Red Army]], the Germans evacuated 60,000<U+2013>70,000 ''Volksdeutsche'' from Ba<U+010D>ka and Baranja to [[Austria]]. Ba<U+010D>ka and Baranja were restored to Yugoslav control when the Germans were pushed out of the region by the Red Army in late 1944. Me<U+0111>imurje and Prekmurje remained under occupation until the last weeks of the war.

==Background==
[[File:Magyarorszag 1920.png|350px|thumb|right|Map showing the difference between the borders of Hungary before and after the Treaty of Trianon. The old Kingdom of Hungary is in green, autonomous [[Kingdom of Croatia-Slavonia|Croatia-Slavonia]] in grey. The population charts are based on the 1910 Hungarian census.]]
{{main|Creation of Yugoslavia}}
At the [[Paris Peace Conference, 1919|Paris Peace Conference]] following the conclusion of [[World War I]], the [[Entente Powers]] signed the [[Treaty of Trianon]] with Hungary after the breakup of [[Austria-Hungary]]. Among other things, the treaty defined the border between Hungary and the newly created [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia|Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes]] (KSCS, later renamed the Kingdom of Yugoslavia). It divided the previously Hungarian-ruled regions of Ba<U+010D>ka and Baranja between Hungary, the KSCS, and Romania, and transferred the Me<U+0111>imurje region and about two thirds of the Prekmurje region from Hungary to the KSCS. Sizable numbers of Hungarians and ''Volksdeutsche'' remained in the areas incorporated into the KSCS.{{sfn|Lemkin|2008|pp=261<U+2013>262}}{{sfn|Pearson|1996|p=95}} Between 1918 and 1924, 44,903 Hungarians (including 8,511 government employees) were deported to Hungary from the territories transferred to Yugoslavia, and approximately 10,000 Yugoslav military settlers ({{lang-sh|''dobrovoljci''}}, lit. volunteers), mainly [[Serbs]], were settled in Ba<U+010D>ka and Baranja by the Yugoslav government.{{sfn|Ungv<U+00E1>ry|2011|pp=75 and 71}} During the [[interwar period]] Hungary agitated for a revision of the borders agreed in the Treaty of Trianon, and relations between these countries were difficult.{{sfn|Lemkin|2008|pp=261<U+2013>262}}{{sfn|Pearson|1996|p=95}}

===Demographics===
Prior to the occupation, the most recent Yugoslav census had been taken in 1931. This census used language as the primary criteria, and counted all speakers of [[Serbo-Croatian]] as [[Serbo-Croats]] rather than recognising distinct [[Serb]], [[Croat]], [[Bosniak|Bosnian Muslim]], [[Macedonians (ethnic group)|Macedonian]] and [[Montenegrins|Montenegrin]] nationalities.{{sfn|Biondich|2008|p=49}} Aligning data on religious affiliation with the linguistic data has been used by scholars to determine approximate numbers of Serbs and Croats in the 1931 census, by counting those of the [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] denomination as Croats.{{sfn|Eberhardt|2003|p=359}}

According to the 1931 census, the territories of Ba<U+010D>ka and Baranja had a combined population of 837,742. This included between 275,014 and 283,114 Hungarians, and between 185,458 and 194,908 ''Volksdeutsche''. Hungarians therefore made up around one-third of the population of these territories, with the ''Volksdeutsche'' comprising slightly less than one-quarter.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|pp=170<U+2013>172}}{{sfn|Ungv<U+00E1>ry|2011|p=70}} According to the historian Dr. [[Kriszti<U+00E1>n Ungv<U+00E1>ry]], the 1931 census showed that the population of Ba<U+010D>ka and Baranja included 150,301 Serbs and 3,099 Croats. This corresponds to a Serb population of about 18 per cent.{{sfn|Ungv<U+00E1>ry|2011|p=70}} These figures vary considerably from the combined Serb and Croat population of 305,917 provided by Professor [[Jozo Tomasevich]], corresponding to 36.5 per cent of the population.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=170}} The 1931 census figures for Me<U+0111>imurje and Prekmurje show a total population of 193,640, of which 101,467 (52.2 per cent) were Croats, 75,064 (38.7 per cent) were [[Slovenes]], and 15,308 (8 per cent) were Hungarians.{{sfn|Ungv<U+00E1>ry|2011|p=70}}
[[File:TerritorialGainsHungary1920-41.jpg|350px|thumb|right|The territorial gains of Hungary in 1938<U+2013>41. The occupied then annexed areas of Yugoslavia are shown in tan in the south ([[Ba<U+010D>ka]] and [[Baranya (region)|Baranja]]) and west ([[Me<U+0111>imurje]] and [[Prekmurje]]).|alt=map showing the Yugoslav and other territories gained by Hungary between 1938 and 1941]]

===Developments 1938<U+2013>1941===
Between 1938 and 1940, following German<U+2013>Italian mediation in the [[First Vienna Award|First]] and [[Second Vienna Award]]s, and the Hungarian invasion of [[Carpatho-Ukraine]], Hungary enlarged its territory. It absorbed parts of southern [[Czechoslovakia]], [[Carpathian Ruthenia]] and the [[Northern Transylvania|northern part of Transylvania]], which the [[Kingdom of Romania]] ceded. One of the ethno-cultural areas that changed hands between Romania and Hungary at this time was the [[Sz<U+00E9>kely Land]]. The support that Hungary received from [[Nazi Germany|Germany]] for these border revisions meant that the relationship between the two countries became even closer. On 20 November 1940, Hungary formally joined the Axis [[Tripartite Pact]].{{sfn|Pogany|1997|p=27}} On 12 December 1940, at the initiative of the [[Prime Minister of Hungary|Prime Minister]], Count [[P<U+00E1>l Teleki]], Hungary concluded a friendship and non-aggression treaty with Yugoslavia. Although the concept had received support from both Germany and [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]], the actual signing of the treaty did not. Germany's planned invasion of [[Kingdom of Greece|Greece]] would be simplified if Yugoslavia could be neutralised.{{sfn|Frank|2001|p=171}} After the [[Yugoslav coup d'<U+00E9>tat|Yugoslav military coup of 27 March 1941]], when the Germans asked the [[Regent of Hungary]], [[Admiral]] [[Mikl<U+00F3>s Horthy]], for clearance to launch one of their armoured thrusts using Hungarian territory, Teleki was unable to dissuade the Regent. Concluding that Hungary had disgraced itself irrevocably by siding with the Germans against the Yugoslavs, Teleki shot himself.{{sfn|Eby|2007|p=15}}{{sfn|Coppa|2006|p=115}} Horthy informed Hitler that evening that Hungary would abide by the friendship treaty with Yugoslavia, though it would likely cease to apply should Croatia secede and Yugoslavia cease to exist.{{sfn|Klajn|2007|p=106}}

==Invasion==
{{main|Invasion of Yugoslavia|Axis order of battle for the invasion of Yugoslavia}}
On 10 April 1941, the [[Independent State of Croatia]] (NDH) was established in Zagreb by the [[Usta<U+0161>e]]. That day Horthy and the new Prime Minister of Hungary [[L<U+00E1>szl<U+00F3> B<U+00E1>rdossy]] issued a joint declaration that Yugoslavia had ceased to exist, releasing Hungary from its obligations under the non-aggression pact and the Treaty of Trianon.{{sfn|Klajn|2007|p=106}} According to the declaration Hungarian troops would act to "protect the Hungarians who live in the south parts from the anarchy" of the [[April War]] which had begun there several days earlier when Italian and German troops invaded.{{sfn|Klajn|2007|p=112}}{{sfn|Ramet|2006|p=137}}{{sfn|Granville|2004|pp=101<U+2013>102}} The following day the [[Third Army (Hungary)|Hungarian 3rd Army]] began occupying those regions of Yugoslavia using the Mobile, IV and V Corps, with I and VII Corps in reserve.{{sfn|Abbott|Thomas|Chappell|1982|p=12}}{{sfn|Wehler|1980|p=50}}{{sfn|Portmann|2007a|p=76}}{{sfn|Thomas|Szabo|2008|p=14}} That day (11 April), the headquarters of the 3rd Army informed that of the [[2nd Army (Wehrmacht)|German 2nd Army]] that Hungarian forces had crossed the frontier north of [[Osijek]] and near [[Subotica]].{{sfn|United States Army|1986|pp=60<U+2013>61}}

The German army's rapid manoeuvres during the invasion had forced the tactical withdrawal of Yugoslav forces facing [[Royal Hungarian Army|Hungarian army]] units and there was no significant fighting between the two armies. The Hungarian forces advanced south to the [[Danube]] between [[Vukovar]] and the confluence with the [[Tisza]] without any real military resistance.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=169}} [[Serbs in Vojvodina|Serb]] [[Chetnik]] irregulars fought isolated engagements,{{sfn|Thomas|Szabo|2008|p=14}} and the Hungarian General Staff considered irregular resistance forces to be their only significant opposition.{{sfn|Komj<U+00E1>thy|1993|p=134}}{{sfn|Cseres|1991|pp=61<U+2013>65}}

On 12 April, the Hungarian 1st Parachute Battalion captured canal bridges at [[Vrbas (town)|Vrbas]] and [[Srbobran]]. Meanwhile, [[Sombor]] was captured against determined Chetnik resistance, and Subotica was also captured.{{sfn|Thomas|Szabo|2008|p=14}} This, the first airborne operation in Hungarian history, was not without incident. The battalion's aircraft consisted of five Italian-made [[Savoia-Marchetti SM.75]] transport aircraft formerly with the civilian airline [[MALERT]], but pressed into service with the [[Royal Hungarian Air Force]] ({{lang-hu|Magyar Kir<U+00E1>lyi Honv<U+00E9>d L<U+00E9>gier<U+0151>}}, MKHL) at the start of the European war.{{sfn|Neulen|2000|pp=122<U+2013>23}} Shortly after takeoff from the airport at [[Veszpr<U+00E9>m|Veszpr<U+00E9>m-Jutas]] on the afternoon of 12 April, the command plane, code E-101, crashed with the loss of 20{{sfn|Szab<U+00F3>|2005|p=196|ps=, citing the obituaries of the "Royal Parachutist Squadron" (13 April) and in the periodical ''P<U+00E1>pa <U+00E9>s Vid<U+00E9>ke'' (27 April).}} or 23 lives, including 19 paratroopers.{{sfn|Neulen|2000|pp=122<U+2013>23}} This was the heaviest single loss suffered by the Hungarians during the Yugoslav campaign.{{sfn|Neulen|2000|pp=122<U+2013>23}}

On 13 April, the 1st and 2nd Motorized Brigades occupied [[Novi Sad]], then pushed south across the Danube into the northern part of Croatian [[Syrmia]] capturing [[Vinkovci]] and Vukovar on 18 April. These brigades then drove southeast to capture the western Serbian town of [[Valjevo]] a day later. Other Hungarian forces occupied the Yugoslavian regions of [[Prekmurje]] and [[Me<U+0111>imurje County|Me<U+0111>imurje]].{{sfn|Thomas|Szabo|2008|p=14}} A later American assessment concluded that German forces had to take the brunt of the fighting, observing that Hungarian forces had "displayed great reluctance to attack until the enemy had been soundly beaten and thoroughly disorganized by the Germans."{{sfn|United States Army|1986|p=65}} When a Yugoslav delegation signed an armistice with German and Italian representatives at [[Belgrade]] on 17 April, the Hungarians were represented by a liaison officer, but he did not sign the document because Hungary was "not at war with Yugoslavia."{{sfn|United States Army|1986|p=64}} The armistice came into effect at noon the next day. News of the success of the Hungarian armed forces in Yugoslavia was welcomed in the Hungarian Parliament.{{sfn|Pogany|1997|p=27}} German forces occupied a narrow slice of northeastern Prekmurje along the German<U+2013>Yugoslav border,{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=84}} which included four ''Volksdeutsche'' villages. In mid-June 1941, this area was absorbed into ''[[Reichsgau Steiermark]]''.{{sfn|Kroener|2000|p=93}}

Hungarian troops suffered 126 dead and 241 wounded during the sporadic fighting,{{sfn|Ungv<U+00E1>ry|2011|p=74}} and killed between 1,122 and 3,500 civilians, including some ''Volksdeutsche''.{{sfn|Ramet|2006|p=137}}{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=169}}{{sfn|Ungv<U+00E1>ry|2011|p=73}} Many civilians were arrested and tortured.{{sfn|Mojzes|2011|p=87}} On 14 April 1941, around 500 Jews and Serbs were bayoneted to death, probably as a warning to others not to resist.{{sfn|Mojzes|2011|p=87}} During post-war questioning, Horthy insisted that he had not wished to invade Yugoslavia, but that he had been compelled to act by disorder and the massacre of Hungarians in Ba<U+010D>ka. Tomasevich has stated that Horthy's claims about disorder and massacre of Hungarians in Ba<U+010D>ka were false.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=169}}

==Geography==
[[File:Hungarian Occupied Yugoslavia 1941 44.png|thumb|right|300px|Map showing the division of the areas of Yugoslavia occupied then annexed by Hungary, including the relevant Hungarian administrative subdivisions|alt=map of the occupied territories and their subdivisions under Hungarian rule]] 
The Hungarian-occupied territory of Ba<U+010D>ka consisted of that part of the [[Danube Banovina]] bounded by the former Hungarian<U+2013>Yugoslav border to the north, the Danube to the south and west, and the Tisza to the west. The occupied territory of Baranja had also been part of the Danube Banovina, but was that area bounded by the former Hungarian-Yugoslav border to the north and west, the [[Drava]] to the west and south, and the Danube to the west. The territory of Me<U+0111>imurje was part of the [[Banovina of Croatia]] prior to the invasion, and was bounded by the [[Mur (river)|Mura]] river to the north and the Drava river to the south. Prekmurje consisted of that part of the pre-war [[Drava Banovina]] that lay north of the Mura.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|pp=62 and 169<U+2013>170}} Most of the Hungarian-occupied territories consisted of flat, largely agricultural land of the [[Pannonian Plain]], except for some hilly country in the northwest of the Me<U+0111>imurje region and in the north of the Prekmurje region.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|pp=172<U+2013>173}} The total area of the Yugoslav territories occupied by Hungary was {{convert|11475|km2|mi2}}, consisting of {{convert|8558|km2|mi2}} in Ba<U+010D>ka, {{convert|1213|km2|mi2}} in Baranja, and {{convert|1704|km2|mi2}} in the Me<U+0111>imurje and Prekmurje regions.{{sfn|Ungv<U+00E1>ry|2011|p=70}}

==Administration==
At first, the occupied territories were placed under military administration.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=170}} The international legal scholar, Professor [[Raphael Lemkin]], who coined the word "[[genocide]]" as meaning the "destruction of a nation or of an ethnic group",{{sfn|Lemkin|2008|p=79}} described the policies implemented by the Hungarian authorities in the occupied territories as "genocidal".{{sfn|Lemkin|2008|pp=262<U+2013>263}} Lemkin asserted that "genocidal" policies were those that were aimed at destroying the political, social, cultural, religious, and economic existence and language of those living in occupied territories.{{sfn|Lemkin|2008|p=79}} In the first two weeks of Hungarian rule, 10,000 Serbs were expelled to the [[Territory of the Military Commander in Serbia]], or the Axis puppet states of the NDH and [[Kingdom of Montenegro (1941<U+2013>1944)|Montenegro]]. On 1 May 1941, the Germans estimated that the population of the territories occupied by Hungary was 1,145,000.{{sfn|Tomasevich|1969|p=76}} On 9 July 1941, the military governor of the town of [[<U+010C>akovec]] in Me<U+0111>imurje, Colonel Zsigmond Tim<U+00E0>r, issued a declaration that the following day Me<U+0111>imurje was to be placed permanently under military administration and Hungarian rule.{{sfn|Kova<U+010D>i<U+0107>|2010|p=62}} According to Professor Sabrina P. Ramet, the government of the NDH consented to Hungarian annexation of the Me<U+0111>imurje area on 10 July,{{sfn|Ramet|2006|p=115}} but according to Davor Kova<U+010D>i<U+0107> of the Croatian Institute of History, the Hungarian declaration was made without consulting with the NDH government, and was never recognized by it.{{sfn|Kova<U+010D>i<U+0107>|2010|pp=62<U+2013>63}} The Croat population were unhappy with the decision,{{sfn|Velikonja|2003|p=164}} and military rule remained in place until 16 August 1941, after which civil administration was introduced. A census of the occupied Yugoslav territories was conducted by the Hungarian authorities in 1941, which counted a total population of 1,030,027. In this census, the ethnic proportions in these territories combined were 37 per cent Hungarian, 19 per cent ''Volksdeutsche'', 18 per cent Croats and 16 per cent Serbs,{{sfn|Ungv<U+00E1>ry|2011|p=71}} and the population of Prekmurje was 102,867.{{sfn|Cox|2005|p=40}} On 14 December, these regions, referred to by Hungary as the "Recovered Southern Territories" ({{lang-hu|D<U+00E9>lvid<U+00E9>k}}),{{sfn|Lemkin|2008|p=631}} were formally incorporated into Hungary and were given full representation in the Hungarian Parliament.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=170}} Although plans to deport 150,000 Serbs (including colonists from the interwar period, but also native inhabitants) to the Territory of the Military Commander in Serbia were opposed by the German command in Belgrade, the Hungarian occupational regime managed to expel between 25,000 and 60,000 of them, mostly to Serbia.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=170}}{{sfn|Ungv<U+00E1>ry|2011|p=75}}{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2008|p=84}}{{sfn|Janjetovi<U+0107>|2008|p=156}} During the war, the Hungarian government resettled some of its pre-war population in Ba<U+010D>ka and Baranja, primarily [[Sz<U+00E9>kelys of Bukovina|Sz<U+00E9>kelys]] from areas of Transylvania ceded to Hungary by Romania in 1940. Between 15,000 and 18,000 were reportedly resettled in Ba<U+010D>ka and Baranja.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|pp=170<U+2013>171}}{{sfn|Ramet|2006|p=138}}{{sfn|Kostanick|1963|p=28}}

The Hungarian authorities established [[concentration camp]]s for Serbs from which they were eventually expelled to the Territory of the Military Commander in Serbia. As part of the "systematic [[magyarisation]]" of these territories,{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=171}} Hungarian political parties and patriotic organisations were encouraged to be active in Ba<U+010D>ka and Baranja, which resulted in discrimination against "less-desirable elements" of the population such as Serbs, Croats and Jews.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=171}} Discrimination extended to education and communication, where Hungarian and German were the only languages permitted in almost all secondary schools, and Serbo-Croat language books, newspapers and periodicals were virtually banned. Well-educated Serbs and Croats were precluded from undertaking work commensurate with their education.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|pp=170<U+2013>171}} Despite this, Serbs and Croats that had lived in the territories prior to 1918 retained their citizenship rights as Hungarians, and some lower-level non-Hungarian public employees were retained in their jobs. One former Serb senator and one former Croat parliamentary deputy sat in the Hungarian Parliament.{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2008|p=84}} In Prekmurje, the Hungarian authorities were more permissive, making no attempt to deport Slovenes in large numbers, and allowing the Slovene language to be used in public.{{sfn|Ramet|2006|pp=136<U+2013>137}}

The ''Volksdeutsche'' of the occupied territories were an important part of the economies of the occupied territories, and by 1941, they were entirely in the thrall of the [[Nazi Party]]. Relations between the occupation authorities and the ''Volksdeutsche'' were strained by the killing of ethnic Germans during the invasion, to the extent that [[Adolf Hitler]] became aware of the issue. The ''Volksdeutsche'' were not active in the Hungarian military or civil administration, but were represented in the Hungarian Parliament, and from 1942 were permitted to conscript their members into the [[Wehrmacht]]. The official organisation of the ''Volksdeutsche'' in Hungary, the ''Volksbund der Deutschen in Ungarn'' (National League of Germans in Hungary), was essentially autonomous during the war, including within the occupied territories.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=172}}

==Districts==
{{See also|Administrative divisions of the Kingdom of Hungary (1941<U+2013>44)}}
Ba<U+010D>ka and Baranja had both been part of the Danube Banovina of Yugoslavia before the war. Me<U+0111>imurje had been part of the Banovina of Croatia, and Prekmurje had been part of the Drava Banovina. Following the occupation, the Hungarian authorities divided the occupied territories between the counties that corresponded with the administrative divisions that had existed when the area had formed part of the [[Kingdom of Hungary]] prior to 1920. These were the [[B<U+00E1>cs-Bodrog County|B<U+00E1>cs-Bodrog]], [[Baranya County (former)|Baranya]], [[Vas County (former)|Vas]] and [[Zala County (former)|Zala Counties]]. The officials in these territories were appointed rather than elected. The counties were further divided into districts, and the authorities reverted many districts, cities and towns to the names used prior to 1920, and in some cases to names which had no historical precedent. Some examples of the name changes in each county are shown below:{{sfn|Jordan|2009|p=129}}

