==The Holocaust==
{{See also|History of the Jews in Hungary}}
<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Destroyed interior of Senta synagogue.jpg|thumb|left|The destroyed interior of the synagogue in Senta (Zenta)|alt=ornate interior of building with columns holding up a mezzanine balcony around the walls, and iron fenced enclosure in the centre of the ground floor. Rubble is strewn on the floor]]   -->
In April 1941, about 23 per cent of Yugoslav Jews (about 16,780 people) lived in the territories occupied by Hungary. These included around 15,405 in Ba<U+010D>ka and Baranja, about 425 in Me<U+0111>imurje, and approximately 850 in Prekmurje.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=583}}

The Hungarian government had passed [[Antisemitism|anti-Semitic]] laws in 1939, and these were applied to the occupied and annexed territories. Initially the laws were applied selectively due to the transfer of the territories from military to civilian administration. Some Jews that had settled in the occupied territories were sent to the Territory of the Military Commander in Serbia where they were placed in the [[Banjica concentration camp]] in Belgrade and subsequently killed. Others were expelled to the NDH where they met the same fate, but it is unknown how many deported Jews died in this way. After the violence of the initial occupation, no further massacres of Jews occurred during the remainder of 1941.{{sfn|Mojzes|2011|p=87}}

The Jews of the occupied territories were subjected to forced labour by the Hungarian authorities, with about 4,000 Ba<U+010D>ka and Baranja Jews being sent to hard labour camps within Hungary, 1,500 Ba<U+010D>ka Jews being among the 10,000 Hungarian Jews sent to perform labour tasks for the Hungarian Army on the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]] in September 1942, and about 600 Ba<U+010D>ka Jews sent to work in the [[Bor, Serbia|Bor]] copper mine in the Territory of the Military Commander in Serbia in July 1943. Only 2 per cent of those sent to the Eastern Front survived the war.{{sfn|Mojzes|2011|pp=89<U+2013>90}}

==Resistance and repression==
<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Partisan gallows in Novi Sad.jpg|thumb|250px|Hungarian soldiers preparing gallows for the execution of Partisans in Novi Sad (<U+00DA>jvid<U+00E9>k) on 25 November 1941|alt=men in uniforms working on a series of posts on a snow-covered square]] -->
In Ba<U+010D>ka and Baranja, the ''Volksdeutsche'' and Hungarian authorities killed significant numbers of Serbs.{{sfn|Prpa<U+2013>Jovanovi<U+0107>|2000|p=58}} After small-scale armed resistance broke out in Hungarian-occupied Ba<U+010D>ka and Baranja in the second half of 1941, the Hungarian military reacted with heavy repressive measures.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=172}} In September 1941 alone the Hungarian occupation forces summarily executed 313 people.{{sfn|Ungv<U+00E1>ry|2011|p=73}} Measures included the establishment of temporary concentration camps at [[Ada, Serbia|Ada]], [[Ba<U+010D>ka Topola]], [[Bege<U+010D>]], [[Od<U+017E>aci]], [[Be<U+010D>ej]] and Subotica, as well as at Novi Sad, [[P<U+00E9>cs|Pechuj]] and [[Baja, Hungary|Baja]]. According to Professor Paul Mojzes, some 2,000 Jews and a large number of Serbs were detained in these camps for periods from two weeks to two months, with Jews that had not been interned being employed as forced labourers.{{sfn|Mojzes|2011|p=87}} Several thousand people remained in camps until the end of the war.{{sfn|Ungv<U+00E1>ry|2011|p=75}} Some of the Jews that had migrated to Ba<U+010D>ka and Baranja during the inter-war period were expelled to the NDH or the Territory of the Military Commander in Serbia where they were killed.{{sfn|Mojzes|2011|p=87}} The [[League of Communists of Yugoslavia|communist]]-led [[Yugoslav Partisans|Yugoslav Partisan]] resistance movement of [[Josip Broz Tito]] was never strong in Ba<U+010D>ka and Baranja because the flat terrain of the region did not lend itself to [[guerilla warfare]], and because [[South Slavs]]'s, from which the Partisans drew their recruits, only made up one-third of the regional population. Some Partisan units raised in the occupied territories were sent to the NDH to reinforce Partisan formations operating there. Despite their initial resistance, the Chetnik movement was largely inactive during the occupation, maintaining some covert activity only.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|pp=172<U+2013>173}} The Partisans and their regional committee had largely been destroyed by the end of 1941.{{sfn|Banac|1988|p=107}} 

In January 1942, the Hungarian army and gendarmerie undertook [[Novi Sad raid|a major raid in southern Ba<U+010D>ka]], during which they massacred 2,550 Serbs, 743 Jews and 47 other people{{sfn|Sajti|1987|p=153}} in places such as Be<U+010D>ej, Srbobran and Novi Sad,{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=172}}{{sfn|Kocsis|Hodosi|1998|p=153}} under the pretext that they were searching for Partisans.{{sfn|K<U+00E1>d<U+00E1>r|V<U+00E1>gi|2004|p=32}} Other sources place the number of Serbs and Jews massacred in Novi Sad as being much lower, at around 879.{{sfn|Granville|2004|p=102}} Raids were carried out in <U+0160>ajka<U+0161>ka (Sajk<U+00E1>svid<U+00E9>k) over 4<U+2013>19 January; in Novi Sad (<U+00DA>jvid<U+00E9>k) over 21<U+2013>23 January; and in Be<U+010D>ej (<U+00D3>becse) over 25<U+2013>29 January. Over the period 4<U+2013>24 January, massacres were carried out by the Hungarian [[15th Light Division (Hungary)|15th Light Division]] commanded by [[Major General]] [[J<U+00F3>zsef Grassy]] and units of the Royal Gendarmerie. The operations were ordered by Grassy, [[Lieutenant General]] [[Ferenc Feketehalmy-Czeydner]], [[Colonel]] [[L<U+00E1>szl<U+00F3> De<U+00E1>k]],{{sfn|Thomas|Szabo|2008|p=14}} and Royal Gendarmerie [[Captain (armed forces)|Captain]] Dr. [[M<U+00E1>rton Z<U+00F6>ldi]].{{sfn|K<U+00E1>d<U+00E1>r|V<U+00E1>gi|2004|p=71}} In addition to Serbs and Jews, members of other ethnicities were also victims: [[Romani people|Roma]] people, a small number of [[White <U+00E9>migr<U+00E9>|Russian refugees]] who had fled [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russia]] after the [[October Revolution|Bolshevik Revolution]], and some local Hungarians.{{sfn|Segel|2008|p=25}} In mid-1942, the [[Yugoslav government-in-exile]] reported that churches had been looted and destroyed, and that [[Serbian Orthodox Church|Serbian Orthodox]] holy days had been prohibited by the Hungarian administration. These reports stated that the Novi Sad camp held 13,000 Serb and Jewish men, women and children.{{sfn|Lemkin|2008|p=263}}

Under pressure from the opposition, the Hungarian government charged 14 Hungarian officers with [[high treason]] in relation to the massacres, including Feketehalmy-Czeydner, Grassy, De<U+00E1>k and Z<U+00F6>ldi. A military trial was held in [[Budapest]] between 23 December 1943 and January 1944, and those that were convicted were sentenced to between 10 and 15 years imprisonment for their part in the massacres. Feketehalmy-Czeydner, Grassy, De<U+00E1>k and Z<U+00F6>ldi were not sentenced as they could not be located, and had fled to Germany.{{sfn|Klajn|2007|p=118}} It is apparent from the trial proceedings that Z<U+00F6>ldi was present during some of the trial.{{sfn|Klajn|2007|pp=125<U+2013>126}} Professor Laj<U+010D>o Klajn has stated that those most responsible for the massacre were not tried before this military court, and that they included Prime Minister B<U+00E1>rdossy and the [[Ministry of Interior (Hungary)|Minister for Interior Affairs]] Dr. [[Ferenc Keresztes-Fischer]], both of whom appeared only as witnesses. Klajn also states that the Chief of the General Staff, [[Ferenc Szombathelyi]] and the Minister of Defence should also have been examined by the court,{{sfn|Klajn|2007|p=124}} that the "genocide had been planned by the highest military and political circles in Hungary for a long time in advance",{{sfn|Klajn|2007|p=126}} and had been intended to convince the [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Germany)|German Foreign Minister]] [[Joachim von Ribbentrop]] that Hungarian troops were needed on its territory instead of the Eastern Front.{{sfn|Klajn|2007|pp=117<U+2013>118}}

==Aftermath==
===German occupation and The Holocaust===
[[File:Spomenik <U+017E>rtvama racije.jpg|thumb|200px|Monument to the 1942 raid victims in Novi Sad.|alt=a sculpture in Novi Sad of three tall gaunt figures dedicated to the 1942 raid victims]]
The occupation of Ba<U+010D>ka and Baranja lasted until 1944. Fearing that Hungary might conclude a separate peace with the Allies, Hitler launched [[Operation Margarethe|Operation Margarethe I]] on 15 March 1944, and ordered German troops to occupy Hungary.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=173}} In the meantime, some of those that had escaped prosecution for the 1942 massacres had joined various German military and police organisations. Feketehalmy-Czeydner had become the highest-ranking foreign officer in the ''[[Allgemeine SS]]'', being promoted to SS-''[[Obergruppenf<U+00FC>hrer]]'' (lieutenant general). Grassy became a SS-''[[Gruppenf<U+00FC>hrer|Gruppenf<U+00FC>hrer und Generalleutnant der Waffen-SS]]'' (major general) and was appointed to command the [[25th Waffen Grenadier Division of the SS Hunyadi (1st Hungarian)]], and Z<U+00F6>ldi joined the [[Gestapo]]. The case against them was re-opened after the German occupation, and in this second trial they were all found not guilty.{{sfn|K<U+00E1>d<U+00E1>r|V<U+00E1>gi|2004|p=155}}

After Germany occupied Hungary in March 1944, the genocidal policies of the authorities were applied comprehensively. Hungarian Jews were subjected to starvation and [[Death marches (Holocaust)|death marches]], and those that had remained in the occupied territories were transported to [[extermination camp]]s. From 26 April 1944, the remaining Jews in Ba<U+010D>ka and Baranja, mostly women, but including children and the elderly, were rounded up into local concentration camps then moved to larger camps in Hungary proper. Between 14,000 and 15,000 Jews from Ba<U+010D>ka, Baranja and other parts of Hungary were collected at Baja and [[B<U+00E1>csalm<U+00E1>s]] then transported to [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]] where most were killed. In September 1944, the workforce of the Bor mine was forced marched for several weeks back to extermination camps where the survivors were killed. One of the two groups of workers numbered 2,500, but only a few survived.{{sfn|Mojzes|2011|pp=90<U+2013>91}}

Such was the extent of the Holocaust in the occupied territories that by the end of the war, nearly 85 per cent of the Jews that had been living in the Hungarian-occupied Yugoslav territories in April 1941 had been killed. This figure comprised about 13,500 Jews from Ba<U+010D>ka and Baranja, and about 1,300 from Me<U+0111>imurje and Prekmurje.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=591}}

===Flight of the ''Volksdeutsche'' and Yugoslav military control===
Several days after the Soviet [[Red Army]] entered the [[Banat (1941<U+2013>1944)|Banat]] on 1 October 1944, the Germans began the [[Flight and evacuation of German civilians during the end of World War II|evacuation of Ba<U+010D>ka]], including the local ''Volksdeutsche''.{{sfn|Wolff|2000|p=152}} With the advance of the Partisans and the Red Army, some of the ''Volksdeutsche'' left the region while some others stayed, despite the situation.{{sfn|Ronen|Pelinka|1997|p=59}} In October 1944, the Banat and Ba<U+010D>ka were captured by Soviet troops. After a few weeks, they withdrew and ceded full control of the region to the Partisans,{{sfn|Ther|Sundhaussen|2001|p=69}} who established an military administration in the Banat, Ba<U+010D>ka and Baranja on 17 October 1944.{{sfn|Portmann|2007b|p=15}} In the first few weeks after Ba<U+010D>ka returned to Yugoslav control, about 16,800 Hungarians were killed by Serbs in revenge for killings during the Hungarian occupation.{{sfn|Kocsis|Hodosi|1998|p=153}} In November 1944, Tito declared that the ''Volksdeutsche'' of Yugoslavia were hostile to the nation, and ordered the internment of those living in areas under Partisan control.{{sfn|Ramet|2006|p=159}} About 60,000<U+2013>70,000 ''Volksdeutsche'' had been evacuated from Ba<U+010D>ka; while an additional 30,000<U+2013>60,000 from Ba<U+010D>ka were serving in the Wehrmacht at the time.{{sfn|Ramet|2006|pp=137<U+2013>138}}

===Return to Yugoslav civilian control===
On 15 February 1945, the Banat, Ba<U+010D>ka and Baranja were transferred from military to civilian  administration with a [[People's Liberation Committee (Yugoslavia)|people's liberation committee]] ({{lang-sh|''narodni odbor oslobo<U+0111>enja''}}, NOO) taking control.{{sfn|Portmann|2007b|p=15}} Until the spring of 1945, the Yugoslav communist administration was characterized by persecution of some elements of the local population, with mass executions, internments and abuses.{{sfn|Ther|Sundhaussen|2001|p=69}} Approximately 110,000 ''Volksdeutsche'' were interned, with around 46,000 dying in captivity due to poor conditions in the camps and the hard labour they were subjected to.{{sfn|Portmann|2007b|p=15}} Victims of the communist regime were of various ethnic backgrounds and included some members of the [[Hungarians in Vojvodina|Hungarian]] and ''Volksdeutsche'' population, as well as Serbs. Hungarian writer [[Tibor Cseres]] has described in detail the crimes he claims the Yugoslav communists committed against Hungarian people.{{sfn|Segel|2008|p=26}} It has been estimated that around 5,000 Hungarians were killed following the return of the occupied territories to Yugoslav control.{{sfn|Portmann|2007b|p=19}} About 40,000 Hungarians left Vojvodina after the war.{{sfn|Eberhardt|2003|p=311}}

===Prosecutions===
After these territories returned to Yugoslav control, the military and national courts in Ba<U+010D>ka prosecuted war criminals and traitors who during the period of occupation had killed about 10,000<U+2013>20,000 civilians. The Security Service of Vojvodina captured the majority of these people. Meanwhile, some of those who were responsible for the 1942 massacres in southern Ba<U+010D>ka were captured in, and extradited from, the newly formed [[People's Republic of Hungary]].{{sfn|Klajn|2007|pp=133<U+2013>136}} In his book ''Ma<U+0111>ari u Vojvodini: 1941<U+2013>1946'' (Novi Sad, 1996), Professor [[S<U+00E1>ndor Kasz<U+00E1>s]] from the [[University of Novi Sad]] listed a total of 1,686 executed war criminals by name, of whom around 1,000 were Hungarian.{{sfn|Portmann|2007b|p=19|ps=. The Hungarian title translates as "Hungarians in Vojvodina: 1941<U+2013>1946".}}

In a third trial in early 1946, the National Court of Hungary in Budapest found Szombathelyi, Feketehalmy-Czeydner, Grassy, De<U+00E1>k, and Z<U+00F6>ldi guilty of involvement in the massacres in the occupied territories, and in carrying out the deportation of Jews to extermination camps. In accordance with the provisions of Article 14 of the Armistice Agreement, the Hungarian authorities then extradited them to Yugoslavia, where they underwent a fourth trial in Novi Sad in October 1946. They were all sentenced to death and executed the following month.{{sfn|Braham|2000|pp=259<U+2013>260}}

===Demographic and political changes===
Of the approximately 500,000 ''Volksdeutsche'' living in Yugoslavia before the war, about half were evacuated, 50,000 died in Yugoslavian concentration camps, 15,000 were killed by the Partisans and about 150,000 were deported to the Soviet Union as forced labourers. They were also stripped of their property. By 1948, only 55,337 ''Volksdeutsche'' remained in Yugoslavia.{{sfn|Ramet|2006|p=159}} Yugoslav Ba<U+010D>ka is now part of [[Vojvodina]], an autonomous province of [[Serbia]], Yugoslav Baranja and Me<U+0111>imurje are part of modern-day [[Croatia]], and Yugoslav Prekmurje is part of modern-day [[Slovenia]].{{sfn|Stallaerts|2009|pp=33<U+2013>34}}

